description.stringValue: Fire-water-powered eclectic tunes and mesmerising visuals, culminating in dynamic dance performances courtesy of the mischievous spirits of Mezcal.
An expression of Bristol’s underground scene, with a heady cocktail of DnB, rave, hardtek and jungle amid a decadent décor with performers challenging hetronormaitve conventions.
“Azaadi” means freedom, and this is the place to feel it; a celebration of South Asian music, culture and spirit under a canopy of vibrant colour.
Family friendly entertainment day and night: Dance, satire, comedy, musical theatre, variety acts, street theatre, interactive games, ground shows.
Posh nosh and soothing sounds next to the Rocket Lounge in the South-East Corner. Book ahead as it gets busy.
In the Glebeland in the Theatre And Circus area featuring dance, satire, musical theatre and variety acts.
The main stage situated on a ley line with the Glastonbury Tor, with an eclectic line up including Sir Rod in the Sunday Legend slot, The 1975, Olivia Rodrigo and Neil Young headlining.
Music venue in the Green Futures Field.
A new venue at the Common, Kinetic is a sanctuary with no music policy. Anything goes! Keeping it loose, playing gems to top up and regroup.
Music and mind expansion is on the agenda in this home for impossible dreamers.
Parading Thursday to Saturday around site and based at the Little Big sound system with NHC DJs in the new Dragon’s Tail Field in the South-East corner next to Shangri-La.
Between Theatre And Circus and the Green Fields with an earthy connection to Eden; a main stage with a host of good time performers – from folk to pop to jazz – and a real ale bar.
Legendary DJ haunt facing The Park’s main stage with a stellar line up of disc spinners in a big tent with a bar.
In the main markets area between the Pyramid and Carhenge; Babylon Uprising deliver thumping underground dance sounds from across the globe.
Directly behind The Pyramid Stage, facing the Tor and Arcadia, with an alternative vibe focussing on the best in dance music, punk, metal, plus new jazz and indie legends.
One of the Festival’s most iconic late-night parties; a collision of fresh talent and heavyweight icons across rap, hip hop, bass, and global beats—no rules, just pure vibes!
Local cider and real ale, plus a cheeky cocktail with DJs till dawn.
An immersive audiovisual arena in Block9 East in the South-East corner, with a colossal, anonymised head - a pseudo-religious monument to our digital, post-truth age.

Short for Generated Oxygen System, a towering concrete-and-glass behemoth in Block9 West in the South-East corner, celebrating the birth and legacy of analogue electronic music showcasing legendary pioneers and fresh talent.
At the centre of the markets between Pyramid and Car Henge, an impromptu performance stage with an eclectic line up day and night.
Two convoy buses each drawn up by a team of winged Pegasus, steered by Olli Ryder and Sons of Acid; four days of electronic music reflecting Manchester’s past, present and future.
A Fem/Queer area aimed at the LBGTQIA+ community and its allies, with a barber, pool hall, cinema and the Mermaid Bar plus Kiki’s, a late-night queer disco/performance space.
Music venue in the Green Futures Field.
Above The Pyramid and Silver Hayes, an immersive cosmological experience with a diverse main stage, plus the ambient Tree Stage, a tree walk, bar, warming fire and jazz grooves in the woods.
Hidden at the back of the NYC Downlow in the South-East corner, The Meat Rack is hot, dark and sweaty and features the ultimate sleazy homo-centric line ups.
Music, demonstrations, talks and Q&As as part of the Science Futures area at the heart of the Green Futures Field.
A cosmic disco at an intergalactic space temple fuelled by out-of-this-world cocktails.
Next to the Acoustic Stage, a riot of make and do, live entertainment and kid-friendly fun.
Groovy sounds curated by Gaz Mayall with a nod to rockabilly, ska and soul, all lurking in the South-East Corner.
In Saxon Market between Silver Hayes and The Other Stage featuring the BBC’s tips for the top plus Radio 1 and 6Music takeovers.
In the Circus Field in the Theatre And Circus area with a spectacular line up of global performers.
Set in Silver Hayes, designed by artist Mr Jago in collaboration with Bristol-based Melissa Wickham, bringing rap, R&B and new electronic sounds.
An impromptu new music stage in Saxon Market just off Silver Hayes.
Music venue in the Green Futures Field.
Next to the Woodsies main stage, an outdoor venue offering deep, immersive ambient sounds and inspiring conversations on ecology and nature from leading musicians, artists, and thinkers.

(Or: How I learned to stop worrying and start disobeying). An interactive museum about apocalypses and how disobedience and organising have saved us from them, both historically, and in the future. Come and see what the end of the world could look like and how to avoid it. Also hosting talks and workshops, and featuring the Hell Bus, a satirical pre-apocalyptic marketing suite about oil company greenwashing by artist Spelling Mistakes Cost Lives.
On the road between The Other Stage and the Theatre And Circus fields, a melting pot of diverse music and irresistible rhythms from all over the globe.
Housed in a stunning dome, LUNA lights up the night with the brightest dance music talent, a space for bass music lovers where every beat is a new orbit. Big Moth Energy!
Music venue in the Green Futures Field.
Set in Silver Hayes, providing a home to the underground sounds from across the area’s music programme.
On the hill between The Pyramid and Woodsies, an all-day dance marathon with DJs in a deserted diner façade.
An unforgettable dancefloor journey set in an ancient amphitheatre protected by a celestial guardian; a DJ space with no hype, no words, and no need to add anything extra.
Where roots run deep, a hotbed of raw sound and rebellion—where music becomes myth and a new generation gathers to worship at the altar of the underground.
An open-air night-club, drawing inspiration from the crossover of architecture, lighting and experimental musical art-forms, at the heart of Silver Hayes to the West of The Pyramid and Other Stage.
Roaring with an eclectic uplifting programme, lost in a lair of dystopian décor bringing unity to the dancefloor with a multi genre journey through sound.
Based at the bottom of the Acoustic Stage field with many first showings of movies, plus Q&As with Hollywood stars and directors.
Surrounded by towering shrines to love, loss and land, an arena pulsing with raw, defiant energy soundtracked by Shangri-La’s most eclectic, boundary-pushing lineup yet.
Not just a stage, it's a movement, The Common’s daytime programme presents The Power of Sound for Collective Liberation.
The space for the underrepresented, where protest and celebration meet united through joy and resistance to party with groundbreaking music collectives.
The daytime debating point in Silver Hayes, a space for discussion and understanding on today’s current affairs and cultural issues.
The space to find everything from healing and future thinking to music, causes and ideas.

In the Green Fields, bringing activism to the forefront to highlight the work of Greenpeace, with installations, a skate ramp, drop slide and a music and performance stage plus the legendary rave tree.
In The Park area with clever, funny, hungover people talking interesting stuff at the Crow’s Nest with the occasional musical interlude.
Stand-up comedy, cabaret, poetry, street theatre, interactive games, sensational and sometimes risqué late-night acts.
On the trek towards The Park from the Other Stage, with DJs ensconced in a huge gyrating dragonfly with lights, fire and magic.
At the east end of the site, above Theatre And Circus and in the same field as the Pilton Palais, with singer songwriters, modern troubadours, icons and legends.
Underground legend Joe Rush’s recreation of the car-henge monument using the carcasses of 24 classic cars. Part sculpture, part free party, alive with drums, DJs, dancing, and defiant joy.
The Park’s centre of well-being and all things good for you in a space where you can recharge body and mind.

A multi-roomed club in a life-size 1982 New York bathhouse-meatpacking warehouse set in the South-East corner, hosted by drag icons, go-go boys, and butchers featuring top international queer underground DJs.
Indoor and outdoor trickery, deckchairs, slackline, trapeze, hoops, juggling and barrels of laughs.
On the walkway between West Holts and The Other Stage with debates, interviews, angsty live music and Billy Bragg’s daily Radical Round-Up.
In the West Holts field with dance lessons, Carnival processions and late-night reverie all with that Latin vibe.
In the Green Futures Field with a full programme of talks and debates from Wednesday to Sunday.
In Bella’s Field in Theatre And Circus with stand ups, music and performance all day till late.
In Bella’s Field in Theatre And Circus with an added element of daring-do and a late night run on the risque.
Set in Silver Hayes, reflecting the heritage and importance of soundsystem culture, showcasing a depth of music inspired by its roots.
On the hill between the Sacred Stones and The Park, a laidback sofa-friendly relaxation zone with a fire pit, bar and stage, remembering Sir Joe Of Strummer.
The Park’s centre of well-being and all things good for you in a space where you can recharge body and mind.
In the Green Fields, an off-grid solar-powered entertainment hub in a main tent and bandstand, plus interactive stalls dedicated to a love of the planet.
At the top of the Theatre And Circus Field, a stopping off point with music and talks on traveller culture.
In the Circus Field in the Theatre And Circus area with bleecher stands and an array of interactive performers.
In Bella’s Field in Theatre And Circus featuring late night excessive antics till 03.00.

In William’s Green at the top of Theatre And Circus, unified by the simple message - NO-ONE IS ILLEGAL. Staffed by actors it’s not 'theatre', it shows films but it’s not a cinema, it sells beer and it has DJs but it’s not a club.
In Bella’s Field in Theatre And Circus with a host of wordsmiths.
